Part 3

By twenty-six, Vikram's name appeared in a major business magazine's "Ones to Watch" list, accompanied by a black-and-white photograph that made him look older than he was. 

By twenty-eight, the same magazine dropped the word "Watch" and simply placed his name among the top young industrialist profiles in the country. 

By twenty-nine, three years running, a Forbes list carried him too. He was always placed somewhere in the lower half, and they always misspelled Ahuja as "Ahluja" in at least one edition, which annoyed Pradhan-babu far more than it ever annoyed Vikram. 

None of this success had happened in the South. Not one factory, not one office, not a single storage unit had been built below the Godavari River. 

That section of his corporate map stayed blank on purpose. Or, more honestly, it was kept blank out of a quiet caution that nobody in the boardrooms had yet dared to challenge him on.

---

The state government's new liquor licensing policy arrived like most government policies do. It was a rumor two months before it was a rule, and a full-blown crisis the week after it was officially signed. 

The policy brought new licensing slabs, higher import duties, and a state minister who had never visited a distillery in his life explaining distillery economics on television with great confidence. 

Pradhan-babu, who was now wearing a second woolen cardigan for winter, aged but refusing to retire, laid the gazette on Vikram's desk. "Sir, if this policy stands as it is drafted, we will lose the Odisha license by March. The margins won't hold."

"Then it won't stand as drafted," Vikram said, without looking up from the figures.

"You are planning to fight the state government in court?"

"I am going to make sure the state government understands what four thousand factory jobs look like on paper before they sign the final draft," Vikram said.

It took eleven months of constant travel, coordination with two national industry associations, one strategically timed press conference in the capital, and a compromise that nobody loved equally. 

In the end, the license survived. Vikram didn't celebrate; he went home, ate a quiet dinner alone, and read the fine print of the amended policy twice, the way some men reread a letter from someone they miss.

---

Ira Sen came to interview him for that same press conference. She worked for the business desk of a mid-size newspaper with ambitions of becoming a national daily. 

She asked sharper, colder questions than the journalists from the bigger papers. 

"Everyone talks about the license survival, Mr. Ahuja," she said, her pen hovering over her notepad. "But nobody is asking what it cost you personally to fight this for eleven months."

Nobody had asked him that in the last year. He looked at her, studying her face. "Is that an interview question?"

"No," she said, closing her notepad. "That one is just for me."

He liked that she said it. The second interview never officially happened; she came back to the office two days later to "fact-check one quote" and stayed for dinner instead, and neither of them ever filed that particular follow-up story. 

She had a way of sitting across a table that made boardrooms feel like a different, distant profession. She would rest her elbows on the dark wood, her chin low over folded hands, watching him the way she watched a source who was about to say something he shouldn't.

"You are doing it again," he told her once as they sat in a quiet cabin.

"Doing what?"

"Interviewing me. Off the record."

"Everything is off the record with you, Vikram," she said, smiling. "Until you decide otherwise."

---

He decided otherwise, slowly, over the course of that autumn. 

Their first evening alone lasted until neither of them noticed that the driver had circled the block four times, waiting for a telephone call that never came.

Streetlight through the car window. Her hand finding the back of his neck, warm and slow, the way she was when she had finished the day's edits.

It was raining when they reached her apartment door. She didn't speak; she took his keys, opened the door, and pulled him inside by his wet collar. 

Her room smelled of old newsprint and jasmine agarbatti. She worked his tie loose before either of them had said a word, her fingers warm against his collarbone.

Some nights they sat on the floor, her head resting against his chest, the city traffic outside dimming to a low hum. She would talk about a headline that had been cut, or the price of paper in Calcutta, and Vikram would listen, holding his glass of water, his shoulders dropping an inch on their own. 

That was the thing the ledger never gave him. Silence that asked for nothing back.

Other nights were faster—her hand tracing his neck in the dark, his mouth finding her shoulder, the dry, clean heat of her skin. They didn't talk about how long it would last. In their profession, you didn't ask for a guarantee before you read the story.

He never told Pradhan-babu why he started leaving the office by eight most evenings. He never told Rohan why he had started smiling at his phone at odd hours, a habit their father would have found, if he had lived to see it, both endearing and faintly ridiculous. 

He gave her, without her asking twice, a supplementary card on his bank account. It was the kind of gesture rich men make when they want love to feel like less of a transaction, and it always, invisibly, becomes one anyway.

---

That October, during the Durga Puja week, she told him she had a special assignment.

"Delhi," she said, packing a small suitcase. "Festive coverage. Three days."

"Take the office car to the airport," Vikram said.

"I'll take a regular cab, don't fuss," she said.

He fussed anyway. He ordered a car for her from the office, complete with a driver, and insisted until she agreed. 

She left for the airport, she said, on Tuesday morning.

On Wednesday afternoon, Vikram's phone buzzed once on his desk. It was a transaction alert, the bank's dry little automated message that he usually cleared without reading. 

*Rs. 340 debited — Café Coffee Day, Salt Lake, near the press building.*

He looked at the screen twice, his brow furrowing. Salt Lake was eleven kilometers from the airport, and considerably farther from Delhi. 

He almost called her. Then he thought: the flight must have been delayed, she is probably killing time near the office before catching a later connection. There was no need to panic.

He had, that exact week, been meaning to give her something. It was a car of her own—not an office-arranged vehicle, but hers. A cream-colored sedan, the keys in his pocket, a small red ribbon still tied in the boot because he hadn't decided yet whether that was too much or exactly enough.

He thought: if she is still in the city, let me surprise her at the office before she leaves. He drove the cream-colored car there himself, leaving his driver behind.

---

The building security guard let him through the gate without question. His face, by then, opened most doors in the city without the need to announce a name. 

Her cabin was on the second floor of the editorial block, glass-walled on one side, with the plastic blinds pulled half-down. The door was ajar. 

He didn't knock. He had never needed to before.

He pushed the door open, expecting to see her at her desk, phone to her ear, ready to be surprised by the keys. 

What he saw instead took his mind a full two seconds longer to process than it should have. It was the kind of two seconds where the body understands the truth before the brain agrees to accept it.

Her blouse, unbuttoned wrong, hung off her left shoulder. 

A man's leather belt lay uncoiled on the floor near the leg of the desk. Rajeev, a junior sub-editor, someone Vikram had shaken hands with twice at office parties and forgotten both times, was leaning over her. 

Underwear—hers, his—was scattered on the carpet without any pretense of having been placed rather than dropped in a hurry. Neither of them heard the door open.

For one full second, nobody in that room moved. Vikram didn't shout. He didn't ask a single question that he already had every answer to. 

He slowly stepped back into the corridor. He closed the door as quietly as he had opened it. If anything, he closed it even quieter, as though the one courtesy left to give them was his silence.

---

Downstairs, the cream-colored car sat exactly where he had parked it near the entrance, the red ribbon still tied in the boot. Vikram stood beside it for perhaps a minute, the hot afternoon sun beating down on his face. 

Nobody watching him would have called the expression on his face rage. It looked, if anything, like simple arithmetic—a accountant solving one final sum before closing the ledger.

He picked up a fist-sized stone from the decorative flowerbed lining the main entrance. He didn't swing it in a fury. 

He brought it down once, deliberately, on the center of the windshield, the glass spiderwebbing instantly. Then he struck it once more on the bonnet, denting the cream paint he had chosen himself two weeks ago after looking at eleven color swatches with an attention to detail he never gave his own wardrobe.

He set the stone down on the driver's seat, almost politely, the way you would return a book you had borrowed. 

He got into his own car, started the engine, and drove away. He left the gift exactly where it stood—wrecked, ribboned, and paid for.

---

Ira came down the stairs forty minutes later, adjusting her earring, laughing at something Rajeev had said in the lift. She stopped dead at the sight of the car. 

The glass lay scattered across the concrete pavement, catching the harsh glare of the streetlights. 

The security guard, an older man named Naresh who had opened that gate for Vikram eleven times that year without ever learning his last name, stepped forward.

"Madam," the guard said, his voice hesitant. "Vikram sir came. He brought this car for you. He left it there, then he left in anger."

Ira said nothing for a long moment, her hand going to her throat. 

Rajeev, standing beside her, asked the question that everyone in that story except Vikram always asks too late. "Did he see us?"

Nobody answered him. Ira was still looking at the red ribbon, soaked now from where the radiator had leaked out beneath the dented hood, still tied in a bow that nobody would ever get to undo.

---

The cream car stayed where it was for three days. 

Vikram's driver, who heard what had happened from the security guard Naresh, was instructed by the accounts office to arrange its recovery. There was a telephone call to the insurance company, a form was dispatched by registered post, and a surveyor's visit was booked for the following Thursday.

Nobody told the vegetable vendors on the pavement outside.

By the second morning, three vendors from the roadside market that ran along the outer wall of the press building had discovered that the flat metal hood of the cream car, which was wide, horizontal, and caught the sun from eight in the morning onward, was ideal for drying red chillies. 

The surveyor arrived on Thursday to find the bonnet spread thick with a deep red layer of chillies, laid out in careful, overlapping rows and smelling strongly of the Andhra sun. A thin woman in a yellow sari was turning them with a stick, her brass bangles clicking with each pass.

She looked at the surveyor with the calm of someone engaged in obvious, purposeful work.

The surveyor made a note in his form, took a photograph, and wrote: *vehicle in use, recovery delayed.* He filed the claim on Friday. The car was eventually towed away ten days after the incident, the cream paint permanently stained along the dent in a crescent of dark red dust.

Naresh, the security guard, told this story to anyone who asked about the car. He told it as a kind of ending, the only one available, because the other ending—the red ribbon, the shattered glass, Vikram's face when he left—was the kind nobody wanted to finish.

---

He never spoke her name again. He didn't mention it to Pradhan-babu, who never asked, nor to Rohan, who heard a version of the story third-hand years later and never brought it up. 

The bank card was cancelled the next morning—a five-minute telephone call, no note, no message. Some silences are just silence; others are the loudest thing a man ever says.

[End of Part 3]
